{"title_page": "Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name     = Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited\n| logo     = BHEL logo.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| type     = [[Government-owned corporation|State-owned enterprise]]\n|traded_as={{BSE|500103}}<br />{{NSE|BHEL}}\n| industry         = [[Electrical equipment]]s\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|1964}}\n| founder          = [[Government of India]]\n| location_city    = [[New Delhi]]\n| area_served      = Worldwide\n| key_people       = Nalin Shinghal <br/> (chairman & MD)<ref name=\"bhel.com\">http://www.bhel.com/financial_information/pdf/16-17/BHEL_AR_2016-17.pdf</ref>\n| products         = \u2022 Gas and Steam Turbines \n\u2022 Boilers\n\n\u2022 Electric Motors\n\n\u2022 Electric Locomotives\n\n\u2022 Generators\n\n\u2022 Heat Exchangers\n\n\u2022 Switchgears and Sensors\n\n\u2022 Automation and Control Systems\n\n\u2022 Power electronics\n\n\u2022 Transmission systems\n| revenue        = {{increase}}{{INRConvert|29474.99|c}} (2017)<ref name=\"bhel.com\" />\n| operating_income={{increase}} {{INRConvert|627.83|c}} (2017)<ref name=\"bhel.com\" />\n| net_income     ={{increase}} {{INRConvert|495.86|c}} (2017)<ref name=\"bhel.com\" />\n| assets         = {{decrease}}{{INRConvert|61230.20|c}} (2017)<ref name=\"bhel.com\" />\n| equity         =  \n| num_employees    =39,821(2017)<ref name=\"bhel.com\" />\n| location_country =  [[India]]\n| homepage         = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited''' ('''BHEL''') owned and founded by the Government of India, is an engineering and manufacturing company based in [[New Delhi]], [[India]]. Established in 1964, BHEL is India's largest power generation equipment manufacturer.\n\n==History==\nBHEL was established in 1964 ushering in the indigenous Heavy Electrical Equipment industry in India. Heavy Electricals (India) Limited was merged with BHEL in 1974.<ref name=ETHistory>{{cite web |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/bharat-heavy-electricals-ltd/infocompanyhistory/companyid-11831.cms |title=Company History \u2013 Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd. |publisher=Economic Times |accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref> In 1991, BHEL was converted into a public limited company. Over time, it developed the capability to produce a variety of electrical, electronic and mechanical equipments for all sectors, including transmission, transportation, oil and gas and other allied industries.<ref name=ETHistory/> However, the bulk of the revenue of the company is derived from sale of equipment for power generation such as turbines, boilers, etc. As of 2017, BHEL supplied equipment contributed to about 55% of the total installed power generation capacity of India.<ref name=\":0\">http://www.bhel.com/financial_information/pdf/15-16/BHEL%20Annual%20Report%202015-16.pdf</ref> The company has also supplied thousands of Electric Locomotives to [[Indian Railway]],<ref name=ETHistory/> as well as defence equipment such as the Super Rapid Gun Mount (SRGM) naval guns manufactured in partnership with the [[Indian Ordnance Factories]] <ref>https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/ordnance-factory-board-develops-advanced-rifles-106010601094_1.html</ref> and Defence Simulators to the Indian Armed Forces....\n\n==Operations==\n[[File:WAG7 of ED BHEL make close-up.jpg|thumb|200x200px|BHEL manufactured locomotive|alt=]]\n[[File:BHEL Swati.jpg|thumb|BHEL Swati]]\nBHEL is engaged in the design, engineering, manufacturing, construction, testing, commissioning and servicing of a wide range of products, systems and services for the core sectors of the economy, viz. power, transmission, industry, transportation, renewable energy, oil & gas, and defence.\n\nIt has a network of 17 manufacturing units, 2 repair units, 4 regional offices, 8 service centres, 8 overseas offices, 15 regional centres, 7 joint ventures, and infrastructure allowing it to execute more than 150 projects at sites across India and abroad. The company has established the capability to deliver 20,000 MW p.a. of power equipment to address the growing demand for power generation equipment.<ref name=History>{{cite web |url=http://www.bhel.com/about.php |title=About us |publisher=BHEL.com |date=31 March 2013 |accessdate=29 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201041654/http://www.bhel.com/about.php |archive-date=1 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBHEL has retained its market leadership position during 2015\u201316 with 74% market share in the Power Sector. An improved focus on project execution enabled BHEL record its highest ever commissioning/synchronization of 15059 MW of power plants in domestic and international markets in 2015\u201316, marking a 59% increase over 2014\u201315.\nWith the all-time high commissioning of 15000 MW in a single year FY2015-16, BHEL has exceeded 170 GW installed base of power generating equipments.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.bhel.com/press_release/press_pop.php?press_id=842 |title=Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd |publisher=Bhel.com |date=2016-04-07 |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n\nIt also has been exporting its power and industry segment products and services for over 40 years. BHEL's global references are spread across over 76 countries across all the six continents of the world. The cumulative overseas installed capacity of BHEL manufactured power plants exceeds 9,000 MW across 21 countries including [[Malaysia]], [[Oman]], [[Iraq]], [[UAE]], [[Bhutan]], [[Egypt]], and [[New Zealand]]. Their physical exports range from turnkey projects to after sales services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bhel.com/about.php |title=Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd.|publisher=Bhel.com |accessdate=2018-05-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201041654/http://www.bhel.com/about.php |archive-date=1 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Initiatives==\n[[File:Manmohan Singh presenting the Scope Excellence Award 2008-09 to the Chairman & Managing Director Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd, Shri B. Prasada Rao, at the MoU Excellence Awards & SCOPE Excellence Awards presentation ceremony.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Manmohan Singh]] presenting the Scope Excellence Award for 2008\u201309 to the Chairman and Managing Director, Shri B. Prasada Rao.]]\nBHEL's investment in R&D is amongst the largest in the corporate sector in India.\n\nDuring the year 2012\u201313, the company invested about Rs. 1,252 Crore on R&D efforts, which corresponds to nearly 2.50% of the turnover of the company, focusing on new product and system developments and improvements in existing products. The IPR (Intellectual Property Rights) capital of BHEL grew by 21.5% in the year, taking the total to 2170.\n\nThe Corporate R&D division at Hyderabad leads BHEL's research efforts in a number of areas of importance to BHEL's product range. Research & product development (RPD) Groups for each product group at the manufacturing divisions play a complementary role. BHEL has established Centres of Excellence for Simulators, Computational Fluid Dynamics, Permanent Magnet Machines, Surface Engineering, Machine Dynamics, Centre for Intelligent Machines and Robotics, Compressors & Pumps, Centre for Nano Technology, Ultra High Voltage Laboratory at Corporate R&D; Centre of Excellence for Hydro Machines at Bhopal; Power Electronics and IGBT & Controller Technology at Electronics Division, Bengaluru, and Advanced Fabrication Technology and Coal Research Centre at Tiruchirappalli.\n\nBHEL has established four specialized institutes, viz., Welding Research Institute (WRI) at Tiruchirappalli, Ceramic Technological Institute (CTI) at Bangalore, Centre for Electric Traction (CET) at Bhopal and Pollution Control Research Institute (PCRI) at Haridwar. Amorphous Silicon Solar Cell plant at [[Gurgaon]] pursues R&D in Photo Voltaic applications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhel.com/about_rd.php |title=Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd.|publisher=Bhel.com |date=2017-03-31 |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n\nSignificantly, BHEL is one of the only four Indian companies and the only Indian Public Sector Enterprise figuring in 'The Global Innovation 1000' of Booz & Co., a list of 1,000 publicly traded companies which are the biggest spenders on R&D in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bhel.com/about_rd.php |title=Research & Development |publisher=BHEL |accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nBHEL is to construct 1340-megawatt coal power plant in Rampal which is close to the [[Sundarban]] mangrove forest for Bangladesh-India Friendship Power Company(Pvt.) Limited (joint venture between [[NTPC Limited]] and [[Bangladesh Power Development Board]]). The project has faced criticism for the environmental impact and the potential harm to the largest mangrove forest in the world.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Khan|first1=Sharier|title=India's Bhel gets Rampal contract|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/indias-bhel-gets-rampal-contract-203518|website=The Daily Star|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shift Rampal power plant, save Sundarbans|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/6480|website=theindependentbd.com|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rampal power plant puts the Sundarbans in crossfire|url=http://www.en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/85947/%E2%80%98Rampal-power-plant-puts-the-Sundarbans-in|website=Prothom Alo|accessdate=18 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314082730/http://www.en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/85947/%E2%80%98Rampal-power-plant-puts-the-Sundarbans-in|archive-date=14 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rampal power plant: A project of deception and mass destruction|url=http://opinion.bdnews24.com/2013/09/19/rampal-power-plant-a-project-of-deception-and-mass-destruction/|website=The Opinion Pages|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rampal plant to doom Sundarbans: Study|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/environment/2013/sep/29/rampal-plant-doom-sundarbans-study|website=www.dhakatribune.com|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref> In 2017 Norway's sovereign wealth fund removed BHEL from its investment portfolio over concerns about the Rampal coal plant.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/environment/2017/05/06/norway-excludes-indias-bhel-rampal-power-plant/|title=Norway excludes India's BHEL over Rampal power plant|date=2017-05-06|work=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2017-05-06|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Industry/e25F6phcfIHlyMSaPlglXP/Norway-wealth-fund-drops-Bhel-out-of-its-portfolio-over-envi.html|title=Norway wealth fund drops BHEL from its portfolio over environmental concerns|last=AFP|date=2017-05-05|work=livemint.com|access-date=2017-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bharathidasan Institute of Management]], a college that functions within the BHEL campus; established in partnership with BHEL\n* [[List of public sector undertakings in India]]\n{{Portalbar|Companies}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{Indian PSU}}\n{{BSE Sensex}}\n{{S&P CNX Nifty companies}}\n{{Public Sector Undertakings in India}}\n\n[[Category:Business schools in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New Delhi]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Gas turbine manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Locomotive manufacturers of India]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of India]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Bombay Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Indian brands]]\n[[Category:Economy of Bhopal]]\n[[Category:Electrical engineering companies of India]]\n[[Category:Industries in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:CNX Nifty]]\n[[Category:BSE SENSEX]]\n[[Category:Economy of Tiruchirappalli]]\n[[Category:Indian companies established in 1964]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1964]]\n[[Category:Rajiv Gandhi National Quality Award recipients]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name     = Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited\n| logo     = BHEL logo.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| type     = [[Government-owned corporation|State-owned enterprise]]\n|traded_as={{BSE|500103}}<br />{{NSE|BHEL}}\n| industry         = [[Electrical equipment]]s\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|1964}}\n| founder          = [[Government of India]]\n| location_city    = [[New Delhi]]\n| area_served      = Worldwide\n| key_people       = Nalin Shinghal <br/> (chairman & MD)<ref name=\"bhel.com\">http://www.bhel.com/financial_information/pdf/16-17/BHEL_AR_2016-17.pdf</ref>\n| products         = \u2022 Gas and Steam Turbines \n\u2022 Boilers\n\n\u2022 Electric Motors\n\n\u2022 Electric Locomotives\n\n\u2022 Generators\n\n\u2022 Heat Exchangers\n\n\u2022 Switchgears and Sensors\n\n\u2022 Automation and Control Systems\n\n\u2022 Power electronics\n\n\u2022 Transmission systems\n| revenue        = {{increase}}{{INRConvert|29474.99|c}} (2017)<ref name=\"bhel.com\" />\n| operating_income={{increase}} {{INRConvert|627.83|c}} (2017)<ref name=\"bhel.com\" />\n| net_income     ={{increase}} {{INRConvert|495.86|c}} (2017)<ref name=\"bhel.com\" />\n| assets         = {{decrease}}{{INRConvert|61230.20|c}} (2017)<ref name=\"bhel.com\" />\n| equity         =  \n| num_employees    =39,821(2017)<ref name=\"bhel.com\" />\n| location_country =  [[India]]\n| homepage         = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited''' ('''BHEL''') owned and founded by the Government of India, is an engineering and manufacturing company based in [[New Delhi]], [[India]]. Established in 1964, BHEL is India's largest power generation equipment manufacturer.\n\n==History==\nBHEL was established in 1964 ushering in the indigenous Heavy Electrical Equipment industry in India. Heavy Electricals (India) Limited was merged with BHEL in 1974.<ref name=ETHistory>{{cite web |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/bharat-heavy-electricals-ltd/infocompanyhistory/companyid-11831.cms |title=Company History \u2013 Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd. |publisher=Economic Times |accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref> In 1991, BHEL was converted into a public limited company. Over time, it developed the capability to produce a variety of electrical, electronic and mechanical equipments for all sectors, including transmission, transportation, oil and gas and other allied industries.<ref name=ETHistory/> However, the bulk of the revenue of the company is derived from sale of equipment for power generation such as turbines, boilers, etc. As of 2017, BHEL supplied equipment contributed to about 55% of the total installed power generation capacity of India.<ref name=\":0\">http://www.bhel.com/financial_information/pdf/15-16/BHEL%20Annual%20Report%202015-16.pdf</ref> The company has also supplied thousands of Electric Locomotives to [[Indian Railway]],<ref name=ETHistory/> as well as defence equipment such as the Super Rapid Gun Mount (SRGM) naval guns manufactured in partnership with the [[Indian Ordnance Factories]] <ref>https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/ordnance-factory-board-develops-advanced-rifles-106010601094_1.html</ref> and Defence Simulators to the Indian Armed Forces....\n\n==Operations==\n[[File:WAG7 of ED BHEL make close-up.jpg|thumb|200x200px|BHEL manufactured locomotive|alt=]]\n[[File:BHEL Swati.jpg|thumb|BHEL Swati]]\nBHEL is engaged in the design, engineering, manufacturing, construction, testing, commissioning and servicing of a wide range of products, systems and services for the core sectors of the economy, viz. power, transmission, industry, transportation, renewable energy, oil & gas, and defence.\n\nIt has a network of 17 manufacturing units, 2 repair units, 4 regional offices, 8 service centres, 8 overseas offices, 15 regional centres, 7 joint ventures, and infrastructure allowing it to execute more than 150 projects at sites across India and abroad. The company has established the capability to deliver 20,000 MW p.a. of power equipment to address the growing demand for power generation equipment.<ref name=History>{{cite web |url=http://www.bhel.com/about.php |title=About us |publisher=BHEL.com |date=31 March 2013 |accessdate=29 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201041654/http://www.bhel.com/about.php |archive-date=1 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBHEL has retained its market leadership position during 2015\u201316 with 74% market share in the Power Sector. An improved focus on project execution enabled BHEL record its highest ever commissioning/synchronization of 15059 MW of power plants in domestic and international markets in 2015\u201316, marking a 59% increase over 2014\u201315.\nWith the all-time high commissioning of 15000 MW in a single year FY2015-16, BHEL has exceeded 170 GW installed base of power generating equipments.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.bhel.com/press_release/press_pop.php?press_id=842 |title=Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd |publisher=Bhel.com |date=2016-04-07 |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n\nIt also has been exporting its power and industry segment products and services for over 40 years. BHEL's global references are spread across over 76 countries across all the six continents of the world. The cumulative overseas installed capacity of BHEL manufactured power plants exceeds 9,000 MW across 21 countries including [[Malaysia]], [[Oman]], [[Iraq]], [[UAE]], [[Bhutan]], [[Egypt]], and [[New Zealand]]. Their physical exports range from turnkey projects to after sales services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bhel.com/about.php |title=Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd.|publisher=Bhel.com |accessdate=2018-05-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201041654/http://www.bhel.com/about.php |archive-date=1 December 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Initiatives==\n[[File:Manmohan Singh presenting the Scope Excellence Award 2008-09 to the Chairman & Managing Director Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd, Shri B. Prasada Rao, at the MoU Excellence Awards & SCOPE Excellence Awards presentation ceremony.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Manmohan Singh]] presenting the Scope Excellence Award for 2008\u201309 to the Chairman and Managing Director, Shri B. Prasada Rao.]]\nBHEL's investment in R&D is amongst the largest in the corporate sector in India.\n\nDuring the year 2012\u201313, the company invested about Rs. 1,252 Crore on R&D efforts, which corresponds to nearly 2.50% of the turnover of the company, focusing on new product and system developments and improvements in existing products. The IPR (Intellectual Property Rights) capital of BHEL grew by 21.5% in the year, taking the total to 2170.\n\nThe Corporate R&D division at Hyderabad leads BHEL\u2019s research efforts in a number of areas of importance to BHEL\u2019s product range. Research & product development (RPD) Groups for each product group at the manufacturing divisions play a complementary role. BHEL has established Centres of Excellence for Simulators, Computational Fluid Dynamics, Permanent Magnet Machines, Surface Engineering, Machine Dynamics, Centre for Intelligent Machines and Robotics, Compressors & Pumps, Centre for Nano Technology, Ultra High Voltage Laboratory at Corporate R&D; Centre of Excellence for Hydro Machines at Bhopal; Power Electronics and IGBT & Controller Technology at Electronics Division, Bengaluru, and Advanced Fabrication Technology and Coal Research Centre at Tiruchirappalli.\n\nBHEL has established four specialized institutes, viz., Welding Research Institute (WRI) at Tiruchirappalli, Ceramic Technological Institute (CTI) at Bangalore, Centre for Electric Traction (CET) at Bhopal and Pollution Control Research Institute (PCRI) at Haridwar. Amorphous Silicon Solar Cell plant at [[Gurgaon]] pursues R&D in Photo Voltaic applications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhel.com/about_rd.php |title=Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd.|publisher=Bhel.com |date=2017-03-31 |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n\nSignificantly, BHEL is one of the only four Indian companies and the only Indian Public Sector Enterprise figuring in 'The Global Innovation 1000' of Booz & Co., a list of 1,000 publicly traded companies which are the biggest spenders on R&D in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bhel.com/about_rd.php |title=Research & Development |publisher=BHEL |accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nBHEL is to construct 1340-megawatt coal power plant in Rampal which is close to the [[Sundarban]] mangrove forest for Bangladesh-India Friendship Power Company(Pvt.) Limited (joint venture between [[NTPC Limited]] and [[Bangladesh Power Development Board]]). The project has faced criticism for the environmental impact and the potential harm to the largest mangrove forest in the world.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Khan|first1=Sharier|title=India's Bhel gets Rampal contract|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/indias-bhel-gets-rampal-contract-203518|website=The Daily Star|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shift Rampal power plant, save Sundarbans|url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/6480|website=theindependentbd.com|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rampal power plant puts the Sundarbans in crossfire|url=http://www.en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/85947/%E2%80%98Rampal-power-plant-puts-the-Sundarbans-in|website=Prothom Alo|accessdate=18 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314082730/http://www.en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/85947/%E2%80%98Rampal-power-plant-puts-the-Sundarbans-in|archive-date=14 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rampal power plant: A project of deception and mass destruction|url=http://opinion.bdnews24.com/2013/09/19/rampal-power-plant-a-project-of-deception-and-mass-destruction/|website=The Opinion Pages|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rampal plant to doom Sundarbans: Study|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/environment/2013/sep/29/rampal-plant-doom-sundarbans-study|website=www.dhakatribune.com|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref> In 2017 Norway\u2019s sovereign wealth fund removed BHEL from its investment portfolio over concerns about the Rampal coal plant.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/environment/2017/05/06/norway-excludes-indias-bhel-rampal-power-plant/|title=Norway excludes India's BHEL over Rampal power plant|date=2017-05-06|work=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2017-05-06|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Industry/e25F6phcfIHlyMSaPlglXP/Norway-wealth-fund-drops-Bhel-out-of-its-portfolio-over-envi.html|title=Norway wealth fund drops BHEL from its portfolio over environmental concerns|last=AFP|date=2017-05-05|work=livemint.com|access-date=2017-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bharathidasan Institute of Management]], a college that functions within the BHEL campus; established in partnership with BHEL\n* [[List of public sector undertakings in India]]\n{{Portalbar|Companies}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{Indian PSU}}\n{{BSE Sensex}}\n{{S&P CNX Nifty companies}}\n{{Public Sector Undertakings in India}}\n\n[[Category:Business schools in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New Delhi]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Delhi]]\n[[Category:Gas turbine manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Locomotive manufacturers of India]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of India]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Bombay Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Indian brands]]\n[[Category:Economy of Bhopal]]\n[[Category:Electrical engineering companies of India]]\n[[Category:Industries in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:CNX Nifty]]\n[[Category:BSE SENSEX]]\n[[Category:Economy of Tiruchirappalli]]\